" lang="en">Global/World Issues</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gclimt"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gsci"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Sciences/Humanities</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gspace"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Life</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">From horror to climate change</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Film-maker Darren Aronofsky takes on nature documentaries with One Strange Rock, about Earth's uniqueness and fragility</Para><Para>He is best known for directing psychological horror films such as the Oscar-winning Black Swan (2010) and last year's much-discussed Mother! - so Darren Aronofsky's decision to make a nature documentary for television may seem puzzling at first.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>But it begins to make sense when you consider that he describes Mother! as a parable about climate change, as told through the story of a married couple whose lives are disrupted by uninvited guests.</Para><Para>Aronofsky, 49, executive-produces One Strange Rock, a 10-part series about the uniqueness and fragility of Earth. Hosted by actor Will Smith, it debuts on the National Geographic channel (StarHub TV Channel 411 and Singtel TV Channel 201) on Saturday at 10pm.</Para><Para>Speaking to The Straits Times and other press in Los Angeles earlier this year, the film-maker promises "a very different show than you've seen before", as far as nature documentaries go.</Para><Para>"There's been shows about animals, about different cultures, about science, (but) what was exciting about this was taking all of it - astronomy, anthropology, biology, chemistry, physics - and trying to blend them together to talk about this home that we're all living in, and all the systems that have to work to make this single spaceship travelling through this huge void work as one."</Para><Para>Besides interviews with eight American astronauts, who offer their singular perspective on the planet after having seen it from outer space, the show - which was more than two years in the making - despatched camera crews to 195 locations across the globe and even in space.</Para><Para>They came back with stunning footage of environments ranging from a cave 400km below ground in New Mexico to the International Space Station soaring 400km above, and a host of extreme locales in between - from the hottest to the coldest spots on the planet.</Para><Para>Aronofsky says his job was to oversee it all, creating "a visual bible that all these different teams could follow, so there was a relationship between the different footage from all over the world that could come together and tell the story of this single home that we're all living in".</Para><Para>The striking visual style of the series will attract younger viewers, he adds.</Para><Para>"I can't tell you the amount of times I've been to a millennial party and they had Planet Earth (2006) and all those BBC shows playing in the background. They're going to be loving this show because of the visuals that these guys pulled off."</Para><Para>Like others involved in the project, the film-maker was driven by a desire to make people more aware of the threats facing the planet, such as resource depletion and disastrous global warming.</Para><Para>"People asked me a lot after I made Mother! if I am an optimist," he says, referring to the film he released last year starring Jennifer Lawrence, which he has described as an allegory about climate change.</Para><Para>"I answered what (the novelist) Margaret Atwood said to me, which was: I am a realist. And I think that's the best answer. You look at the evidence and it's disheartening, especially with what is happening today."</Para><Para>Raising awareness of the problem, however, is the first step towards potentially changing this bleak future.</Para><Para>"There is a silver lining in the sense that it's finally very clear what we are battling and what we are fighting for. People are stepping up and corporations are stepping up and cities and governors are stepping up.</Para><Para>"And the means for our survival exists," says the director, who has an 11-year-old son with his former partner, actress Rachel Weisz, 48. "Finally, clean energy is cheaper than fossil fuel in many places on the planet."</Para><Para>"And so I do have hope."</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Alison de SouzaIn Los Angeles </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Crew filming on the glaciers of Svalbard (above); Africa and the Indian Ocean as seen from the International Space Station; and a bend in a river as seen from space. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></Adoc